"America/Los_Angeles"},"updated":"2013-07-05T20:04:33.865-0500","status":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/status/6","description":"The issue is considered finished, the resolution is correct. Issues which are closed can be reopened.","iconUrl":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/images/icons/statuses/generic.png","name":"Closed","id":"6","statusCategory":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/statuscategory/3","id":3,"key":"done","colorName":"green","name":"Done"}},"components":[],"timeoriginalestimate":null,"description":"Originally posted by Antti Haapala on 2012-05-02 08:56:35.517547+00:00\n\nEven if I bundle without --all (Bundle all directories (including mounted filesystems), a filesystem on Linux mounted at /data/, and visible in /proc/mounts, /etc/fstab etc, is also rsynced within the image! Furthermore, if I exclude the directory with -e /data/ (which I should not have to do for all directories), then the resulting image does not have the mountpoint at all.\n\nI propose that where available, without --all, euca-bundle-vol should really hard to try to not sync mounted filesystems, but still retain the mountpoints; also using --one-file-system on Linux, or actually iterating all mount points (there can be bind mounts too; those should not copied either.","customfield_13000":null,"customfield_13200":null,"customfield_11300":null,"customfield_11500":null,"timetracking":{},"customfield_10005":null,"customfield_10401":null,"customfield_10600":null,"customfield_12900":null,"attachment":[],"aggregatetimeestimate":null,"summary":"euca-bundle-vol rsync crosses filesystems","creator":{"self":"https://eucalyptus.atlassian.net/rest/api/2/user?username=eucabot","name":"eucabot","key":"eucabot","accountId":"557058:007ef05d-c772-4437-b383-d2b42d2a88a7","avatarUrls":{"48x48":"https://avatar-cdn.atlassian.com/9e6d2b33ee28ce1387b2aa6cbe935cf3?s=48&d=https%3A%2F%2Feucalyptus.atlassian.net%2Fsecure%2Fuseravatar%3FownerId%3Deucabot%26avatarId%3D12